Okay so there are a lot of different types of physics. Why? Because physics covers everything, and it's easier to focus on one area at a time.

Here's the simple breakdown:

**Classical Mechanics** - How things move. Gravity, motion, pushes, pulls. This is what you think of as basic physics. A ball rolling, a car driving, planets orbiting. {{viz:diagram-02}}

**Thermodynamics** - Heat and temperature. Why things heat up, cool down, how energy spreads. Your oven, your fridge, why you sweat.

**Electricity & Magnetism** - Electricity and magnets. How they work, how they affect each other. Your phone battery, the Earth's magnetic field, lightning.

**Waves & Optics** - Sound, light, vibrations. How light travels, how sound moves, why rainbows happen. The sky being blue, your speaker making sound.

**Quantum Mechanics** - How tiny things work (atoms, electrons, particles). This gets weird—things behave differently at tiny scales. {{viz:anim-01}}

**Modern Physics** - Super fast stuff and extreme conditions. Relativity (Einstein's stuff), nuclear reactions, particle physics. Black holes, nuclear energy.

Each branch has its own rules and its own focus. But they all follow the same basic idea: observe → understand → predict. {{viz:chart-01}}
